story:
Welcome Adventurers!

My name is Alex. This isn't my first rodeo. Back in 2014 I did my first 24 hour livestream for Macmillan Cancer Support and since then my community has raised over £2000 for a charity that's very close to my heart. I work for Macmillan for 3 1/2 before I made my start in my current career path and the work that they do is simply incredible.

After what's been a brutal year for us all, and especially charities, we need to help those who are not only in the world of Covid-19, but are fighting cancer at the same time. I'm here to change that in 2021.

On August 28th, 2021 I'll be reinstating our yearly 24 hour livestream event. There'll also be a teaser livestream on Saturday 3rd April, which is the Easter weekend.

There’ll be giveaways, challenges, singing, discussion and more.

Until then, the donation page is open to donate if you can’t make it on the day. You can also drop by on any livestream before the events to hit the follow button to make sure you’re ready to catch the event, or use the Game Heroes donation link!

Roll for Initiative.
A

We sadly lost Dad to cancer on Christmas Eve and yet he only began to feel unwell in early November. He was at home with family and at peace.  We have to be thankful that his fight was short and not a long, drawn out battle but his loss has devastated the family.  The MacMillan team where there with support at one of the worst times in our lives, made even more challenging with this pandemic!

A man full of life and cheer and invariably with a pint of ale in his hand, Dad loved nothing more than good company and, unsurprisingly, good beer.

Please help us to show our support for MacMillan and the amazing work that they do. The challenges that they face and the emotions of family members that they have to witness must make their work so so hard.  They have our utmost respect and our heartfelt thanks for all that they do.

RIP Dad

story:

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. As you know, my husband to be, Alexander Wilson, passed away on Sunday 13th December 2020 following a short, but very difficult battle with lung cancer. Alex was a loving, caring, compassionate, gentle, kind soul, and was dedicated to his family and friends. He is the bravest and most selfless person I have ever had the pleasure of meeting. Alex fought tremendously throughout his battle with lung cancer, a battle that nobody should ever have to. He has shown us what true courage and strength really means. He gave it his all, and fought until his very last breath. We miss him dearly!

We are fundraising in memory of Alex, with the money raised going to Macmillan cancer support. They supported Alex every step of the way, and we wish to give back to them. It would mean a lot to us if people who wish to could donate what they can, every little really does help. It will help other families going through this difficult journey and give them that extra support that they really need!

We thank you, 

With love, Shannon and all of Alex's family and friends

story:
4 years ago my beloved Nan (Kathy Blackwell) sadly passed away from Cancer, her battle was a largely unpleasant one, but was made slightly better thanks to the superb team of Macmillan nurses, who worked tirelessly around the clock to make sure she was looked after in the best possible way.

In 2018, they reached an estimated 880,258 unique people affected by cancer through Macmillan Nurses, of which the majority were people living with cancer. There expert nurses offer much-needed advice, information and support to people with cancer.

I want to give back to Macmillan, to give a small thank you for the work they done, not just for my Nan, but for the whole family in what was a tough time for us all. I have set myself a challenge of running 200km between 4th January - 31st January, which is on average 7.14km a day. This challenge is not only rewarding for me but hopefully raise vital funds for Macmillan

Please help me reach my fundraising target by giving whatever you can, any donation is more than appreciated. Thank you in advance for your generosity.

pageSummary: Help us raise vital funds because of the COVID19 pandemic
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit the Bake5, Care5, Donate5 JustGiving page #BCD5 

Please help raise vital funds for St John Ambulance to allow them to carry on with their life saving work during COVID19, by following these 4 steps:

  • BAKE 5 cupcakes. Keep busy and have fun with family. Take a break from home schooling. 
  • CARE for 5 friends. Mental health is so important, especially during lockdown. Check-in with five friends or consider those alone and ask how they are.
  • DONATE £5 to St John Ambulance.
  • SHARE your images; use the hashtag #BCD5, nominate 5 friends and share this JustGiving page to keep raising money

https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising-edit/bakecaredonate5

These selfless volunteers are putting their lives at risk to help us. They are supporting the NHS by providing ambulance and care facilities and some of their volunteers are even re-training to be able to help deliver the new vaccines. 

Who are we? Christopher & Gemma; we got married during COVID19 in November. Gemma is a doctor working in Intensive Care in London, having been redeployed for the second time since the COVID19 pandemic started. Christopher is a volunteer and supporter of St John. 

Please make sure you follow the government guidelines in your local area when undertaking this challenge.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
So today (7th January) should have been my stepdad’s 74th birthday. We all know that 2020 was a challenge and the year took a turn for the worse for our family in November, when Alan passed away very suddenly at home. 

For that reason I’m hoping to walk (or maybe even run!) 74k during the month of January- a km for each year of his life (almost!) 👟

 It’s not quite an ‘Ironman’ challenge but from a pretty much horizontal start (involving too many sofa days and too much pavlova), it’s still going to challenge me! I’m not going to count my usual daily steps in that 74k- that would feel like cheating! It has to be in addition to the usual steps I do whilst working and wrangling three children...🤪 

For me, the challenge will be fitting it in! 

Therefore, I’m likely to be hitting the pavements in the cold, damp evenings to rack up the kms.

In fact, after a chilly walk on Saturday that turned out to only be 2km, I started thinking that 74km was actually quite a long way! 

Selfishly, it might get me a little bit fitter after sloth-ing about all Christmas! 🦥 

 Also, Alan loved walking, so it seems appropriate. 

Any pennies I raise will be donated to the British Heart Foundation. Every little helps towards research into heart and circulatory diseases and their causes. 

Thank you  Xx 



Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks.

story:
We have lost our hero Alan Cotterill, devoted husband, loving Dad, Grandpa, brother and friend.

He was our world and family to Alan was everything. 

Thanks to the work of the British Heart Foundation, he was granted his wish of ‘just another couple of years’ to watch his grandchildren grow up, and for this we are all eternally grateful.

Help us to raise money for the BHF in order for other families to live their lives to the fullest and experience as much love as we have had.

He was fit and healthy and exercise was a major part of his life.  Despite having had regular health checks, including a thorough check of his heart, no underlying issues had been found.  We want to raise funds in his memory to fund research into heart disease and heart attacks so that others may not have to suffer the pain of losing someone so wonderful.

story:
My Step Challenge is a fun and simple way to raise money for the BHF. With every pound you raise and your support, we will be closer to beating heartbreak forever. 

On 2nd of July 2019, my dad aged 58 passed away from a sudden heart attack. Understandably this devastated my family and it is only now that I have found the strength to do something for such a pivotal cause. My brother also has a congenital heart defect which has also impacted all of our family’s life, and I wanted to raise some money to help the BHF whose work has done so much for my family already. 

Any donations are welcome given such challenging times, but it would mean so much to me to reach this target.

story:
Last April 2 months after his 35th birthday I lost my first Nephew Matthew. He was funny caring the dad of 2, and family meant everything to him. This left the whole family heart broken especially my sister Matthews mum & dad, and Nick his brother. He is missed by us all so much.

Anything I can raise is going to a great cause and I thank you for what ever you can donate. 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
We are delighted to announce that our partnered charity for #2021 is the British Heart Foundation. 

In March of 2020 one of our founding members, Stephen Morley was taken into the Royal Brompton Hospital, London to have life saving open heart surgery. He was only 29 years old and was suffering with a genetic disorder. With the support of the Royal Brompton staff Stephen is making excellent progress. 

It is clear to see why we chose this charity and are looking forward to helping in any way we can to promote their message, spread awareness and raise as much money as possible for life saving research.

We are aiming to live stream our online gaming antics via Twitch for 24 hours.

We start at 8pm on Thursday 28th January 2021 and finish 8pm on Friday 29th January 2021.

eventName: KATHERINE RUNS 60K FOR 60 YEARS OF THE BHF
pageSummary: I am running because the work we do matters to so many
pageSummaryWhy: the work we do matters to so many
story:
I am not a runner...

However, I spent lockdown (part 2) taking part in the Couch to 5K programme and have decided to set myself a challenge in lockdown part 3. 

As some/most people know I am a Fundraising Manager for The BHF. Over the past several months I have watched my team and wider colleagues work tirelessly to try and raise funds to continue the amazing work that The BHF does. Covid 19 has affected everyone, but for the charity sector it has been devastating. There have been many hard moments (and continue to be) including redundancies and income we had worked so hard to secure disappearing overnight. Also looking outside of The BHF to the wider charity sector at former colleagues and friends who have lost jobs. People who work in an industry because they love it and now due to the pandemic and will now struggle to find new roles. 

I have decided therefore to do ‘my bit’ outside of the day job and want to set myself the challenge to run 60k in February, which is National Heart Month as well as The BHF turning 60 in 2021. Having just run my first 5k in 3 years today, this won't be easy, if it was it wouldn't be a challenge! 

So, to summarise I am doing this for a few reasons;

-    Health
-    Keeping sane at a tough time
-    For my BHF North West Team
-    To raise awareness to support the charity sector in general at this tough time

If anyone could make a donation I would be very grateful. I see daily how the money people give to The BHF changes and saves lives. Without them the world would look very differently, and I am passionate to play my small part to make a difference. If anyone out there would be keen to do something similar for The BHF or another cause close to your heart, I would encourage you to do so. If everyone did something, no matter how small it would make the world of difference. 

Thanks in advance to any support you can offer at a challenging time

Kat

story:
As everyone knows..(well almost everyone) I have a MASSIVE love for chocolate and I eat it on a daily basis, and I tend to have salted caramel chocolate the most! 

I have decided to give up chocolate for 1 month to try and raise money.

If you’d like to donate any amount is much appreciated because I am going to be testing my willpower to the max because I can’t resist a delicious piece of chocolate 😍🍫

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: I am giving up Chocolate, Sweets & Fizzy Drinks because I want to challenge myself.
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up Chocolate, Sweets & Fizzy Drinks
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. YES, I am giving up for the whole of March, Chocolate, Sweets & Fizzy drinks for The BHF. They have helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
pageSummary: I am giving up chocolate and sweets for March because I want to raise money and get healthier
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up chocolate and sweets for March
pageSummaryWhy: I want to raise money and get healthier
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. My beautiful Phoenix gave her heart to save lives so it’s a no brainer for  me to make a small sacrifice to raise vital funds ♥️ It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks so much 💝

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummaryWhy: Of my ❤️ health and the ❤️ health of others
story:
Being pregnant during lockdown was frankly a disaster for my weight and fitness. At the end of 2019 I ran 50miles in October by October 2020 I had my precious girl but couldn't walk up stairs without getting out of breath. This year I'm pressing the reset button and I'm going to Do a health/fitness challenge every month. In March I'm doing dechox for myself with the added bonus of raising money for The BHF 😄

BHF: "The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now."

story: Thank you for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF are such an important charity and mean so much to me as I lost my mum to a heart condition nearly nine years ago and I don't want anyone to go through the same thing as me but unfortunately they still do. The BHF have helped half the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every penny counts so please give what you can to help. Thank you

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
pageSummary: I am running because sight loss shouldn't mean lifestyle loss
pageSummaryWhy: sight loss shouldn't mean lifestyle loss
story:
This will be my fourth time running LLHM and my third time for charity - I love the personal challenge of running half marathons and doing it for charity makes it all the more rewarding. All donations are appreciated, I don't think I can make a case for Guide Dogs better than the charity themselves so please read the below from them:

In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation. Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss. We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

Thank you for taking the time to read this page and a very big thankyou if you decide to donate!!

story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

We will also run our charity mystery box to raise a further £500 towards this charity event, giving us a grand total of £1500 to donate to Great Ormond Street Children’s Hospital.

This will take place live on 17th January 2021

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story: We spent 8 months at the amazing Great Ormond street hospital with Jamie. I have never encountered a hospital like it. The staff, the feel, the dedication, the support and the medical care are beyond description. It became home and our safe place at the scariest time of our life. The staff became family and even when we knew we had to leave without the news we were hoping for, the support continued. We would love all donations made to GOSH to be in one place and in Jamies memory. This is a way to do it and we thank you all so much for your past and future support. We really hope to help, even in a small way, families who are going through their ordeal in this incredible place x

pageSummary: I am hosting an online concert because they took care of me when I was poorly
pageSummaryWhat: I am hosting an online concert
pageSummaryWhy: they took care of me when I was poorly
story:
Dear friends and family, 

I am hosting an online concert on 23rd January to celebrate my 10th birthday and my brother Max’s 8th birthday. 

I don’t need any presents, I want do something memorable and meaningful. I want to raise fund for my chosen charity Great Ormond Street, because when I was four I had pneumonia, they helped me recover and get through the hard time. I want to give something back, so they can help more children in need. 

My brother and I also wish to cheer everyone up in lockdown. Max will be performing with me in the concert, we will be playing some lovely piano and violin tunes, hope our music can bring you some joy during this difficult time. 

We will really appreciate any small donation you can make, but you don’t have to donate, we just hope you enjoy our music. 

We wish you a happier and healthier 2021!
Lots of love 

Phoebe 

xx

story:
Dear friends and family, 

Hope you are all keeping well!

I am hosting an online concert on 23rd January to jointly celebrate my 10th birthday and my brother Max’s 8th birthday. 

I don’t need any presents, I want to do something memorable and meaningful to make this birthday very special. I want to raise funds for my chosen charity Great Ormond Street, because when I was 4 years old  I had pneumonia, they helped me recover and get through the tough times. All I remember now is the happy times in the hospital! I want to give something back to them, so they can help more children in need. 

My brother and I also wish to cheer everyone up in lockdown. Max will be performing with me in the concert, we will be playing some of our favourite  piano and violin tunes, hope our music can bring you some joy during this difficult time. 

I really appreciate any small donation you can make, but you don’t have to, we just hope you enjoy our music. 

Topic: Phoebe & Max 2021 Lockdown Birthday Concert 
Time: Jan 23, 2021 02:00 PM London 

Join Zoom Meeting 
https://us04web.zoom.us/j/8057088516?pwd=aHR2L2MydnA5eEJPNFRybDBVSEJhUT09 

Meeting ID: 805 708 8516 
Passcode: BeHappy 

We wish you a happier and healthier 2021!
Lots of love 

Phoebe

pageSummary: I am toddling awkwardly because of my brother Liam.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Hi everyone

I don’t run I toddle like a toddler. I’ve decided to really go out of my comfort range again this year and by running 10k around the London landmarks for Great Ormond Street Hospital. 

For those who know me, you know what my family went through with Liam back in 2012 and also my personal struggle with losing him. Liam had a rare lung disease Pulmonary Hypertension Veno-occlusive disease. He was the youngest person with the disease as far as we know.  Since his diagnosis and passing his case has gone on to allow a path of investigations and studies on how this disease can be treated but it is still treated by lung transplant but also on how to get an early diagnosis.

 2020 was a year which made everyone feel heavy  sadness and think of the loved ones who are no longer with us. Which is why this is so important. 

When I was younger I spent time at GOSH as a patient but it was with Liam where most my days were spent. To be able to sleep meters away from Liam and stay up with him and meet his heroes such as Frank Lampard it wouldn’t have been possible without GOSH Charity. My final memories of Liam were spent at at his bedside and they are memories I will treasure forever. 

This years challenge is a larger step ahead than last years. I’ve plucked up the courage to do something bigger. 

Any amount is generous enough, but my minimum amount to raise is £250 but more would mean be so much more so spare pocket change is welcome too!  Remember this is not only for  me but in memory of Liam, he was the most selfless, loving and caring young man and also to enable GOSH to provide a place to stay for those families who have a loved one at GOSH. 

Lots of love and thank you 

Sam xx

pageSummary: We are walking 500 miles because we want to beat cancer!
story:
Did you know...
Cancer Research was forced to cut vital research by a whopping £45m due to COVID-19?

The cuts equate to:

  • 12 fewer fellowships
  • 24 fewer research programmes
  • 68 fewer projects
  • circa 328 fewer researchers

All of us have been impacted by Cancer in some shape or form as it is the second leading cause of death globally. We all have our own story to tell.

Help us make a difference!
A small team of us at BT have committed to collectively walking 500 miles by the end of the financial year (Wednesday 31st March). To put into perspective, this is roughly the distance of London to Iverness (actually a bit more).

If we have more people sign up to join our group, then in true Proclaimers style, we won't be stopping at 500 ...

Please support us by donating anything you can.
THANK YOU!

James, Rita, David, Tom, Sarah, Bijal and Ian

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Thanks for supporting our fundraising for Marie Curie.

Information and Resources:

Marie Curie provide care and support for people living with
terminal illness. They also assist the families of those who are unwell, and tend to their needs. Last year they cared for over 40,000 people across the UK.

  • £20 – could pay for one hour of vital nursing care for someone
    living with a terminal illness in the comfort of their own home.
  • £90 – could pay for half an evening’s care in a person’s home
    when they need it most.
  • £180 – could provide nine hours of nursing support in someone’s home through the night, bringing the expert care and comfort families need in very challenging situations.

story:
ABOUT ME...
I AM OVERWEIGHT.
Currently, more so than ever before.

My story isn’t exciting, unusual or complicated - but thanks to a life of wacky hormones, pregnancy, a fair amount of IVF over the past six years and now, yet another Lockdown (and let’s be honest, general laziness and poor choices!) - I have continued to gain more and more weight.

Throughout my life, weight loss has constantly been a thing. It’s always been there, in the background. There have been many diets, eating plans, dieticians, clubs, supplements, bootcamps etc... you name it. Off and on, weight has certainly been lost over the years, but never in significant amounts - and those little bits and pieces of weight loss have always been regained soon after, plus a bit extra each time!

THE PLAN...

So, here’s where you come in...


I would like your help to change my life.
I would also like to do more for this amazing charity.
So why not combine the two?
I would like to LOSE WEIGHT and DONATE 
Your £s for my lbs!

I do not want to let Marie Curie down.
I do not want to let you all down either.
By doing this for myself and for my loved ones and also by doing something for this great cause - I hope to raise as much money and of course, lose as much weight as possible.
As I will be doing this with you all in mind and in memory of my lovely Dad, it will hopefully give me the motivation I need to stick to this, once and for all - and finally do what I need to. 
NO EXCUSES!

***My weight loss target is 4st/56lbs/26kg***

There will not be an unachievable time limit.
There will not be a crazy fad diet.
There will not be any starving involved.
We’re talking a healthy, maintainable, lifestyle change - good nutritious meals and some manageable daily exercise.

Please help me out and DONATE.
It doesn’t need to be a huge amount.
Even £1 tells me that you’ve read my story and that you’re onboard. By donating you’re not only helping Marie Curie, but you’re also helping to keep me out of the biscuit tin!

If you would like to follow my progress, please follow my Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/heymumblog/
I will update the page with updates and following my weekly weigh-ins.

THE CHARITY...
🌼 MARIE CURIE HOSPICE, NEWCASTLE 🌼

Marie Curie is where my Dad spent the last days of his life. It is where we spent my Son’s first and my Dad’s last Christmas together as a family. Not only did they care for Dad, but they also cared for us as a family during the most difficult of times. They guided us, fed us, allowed us to sleep over and also helped us set up baby changing and feeding areas for a young baby, to try and make things easier for us.
Marie Curie offer specialist care and support for people living with a terminal illness and their families. They’re an outstanding hospice, providing inpatient and outpatient support and have day services covering various aspects of palliative care, including symptom management, rehabilitation, psychological support and care at the very end of life. Marie Curie are there to help people with serious illnesses to have the best quality of life possible, whatever that might mean for them. The hospice team includes doctors, nurses, physiotherapists, social workers and many more, and is supported by over 100 volunteers, who play a vital role in the running of the hospice. Some people stay in the 20 bed in-patient unit, where relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night, and stay with their loved ones if they wish. The day therapy unit offers outpatient clinics and a wide range of activities and therapies, including baking, art therapy and relaxation. They also provide support for carers and families, including a social work team who provide emotional and practical advice. The chaplain is also there to provide spiritual care to patients and their loved ones.

Thank you for supporting Marie Curie, and helping them to make sure more people with a terminal illness in the Newcastle area get the care and support they need.

THANKS FOR READING AND THANK FROM THE BOTTOM OF MY HEART FOR YOUR LOVE AND SUPPORT.

Steph X

pageSummary: Beth, Abbie and Mark because we sadly lost our Mum/fiancé to cancer.
pageSummaryWhy: we sadly lost our Mum/fiancé to cancer.
story:
As many of the people reading this will know, Mum battled against cancer for nearly 5 years. She was brave, strong and a fighter. We couldn't have been more proud of her for the strength and courage she showed throughout. Sadly on 5th January 2021 she lost her battle and we had to say goodbye to the most amazing Mother, Fiancé, Sister, Auntie, Mama and Granny-to-be.

Mum always said that she would never want a house full of flowers when the time came. As a family we have decided to make donations in Mum's name to Marie Curie, they are a donation based charity that helps and supports people and families going through the same battle that we have faced. 

Every donation will make a donation a huge difference to this charity and it will mean the world to all of us.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
The Marie Curie Bradford Hospice supports people living with a terminal illness and those closest to them to live as well as possible. The Hospice is often very different from what people expect it is a warm, friendly space with beautiful gardens, delicious home-cooked food and personalised care. Every person is treated as an individual and helped to reach their goals and fulfil their wishes. A team of nurses, doctors, social workers, physiotherapists, chaplains, bereavement counsellors and pharmacists work together, putting every person at the centre of their care. Throughout Covid-19 Bradford Hospice teams have been working around the clock to continue supporting local people. Death, dying and bereavement is at the forefront of peoples minds and Marie Curie knows what a difference the right care at the end of life can make. They cant do any of this without your support. Thank you for your generous donation which supports the Bradford Hospice and Marie Curie care.

  Personally my mother was cared for there and was treated with much kindness and respect.  I will be 80 when I do this Trek and I continue to train and keep fit for it.  At this very difficult time during the Covid Pandemic it is so difficult to raise money for the Hospice.  Please consider donating to this great cause.

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Me and Pat’s Daughters and grandchildren are going to run the Liverpool Roll n Roll 5k, in memory of a very brave mum and Nan who sadly past away last November to the horrible disease of Cancer. And we want to do something for as a family to say thank you too Marie Curie staff for all their hard work in Pats Final days... we can not say thank you enough but hopefully us do this,  that will be hard for some of us but as a family we want this Challenge to so thanks.

Hopefully fingers crossed this event will take place....

At the Marie Curie Hospice, Liverpool, we give expert care to people with a terminal illness, and their loved ones every day of the year. Our hospice team includes doctors, nurses, physiotherapists, social workers and many more, and is supported by local people who freely volunteer their time and energy to help us run the hospice.As well as being a place where people can stay to get the expert care they need in a friendly and homely setting, we also support people visiting with clinics and therapies. These include yoga, exercise classes and relaxation. People using the day unit can also get together over a freshly cooked lunch from our chefs.Relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night, and stay with their loved ones if they wish to. We need to raise £6,397 per day to run the hospice, so every penny counts. Thank you for helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in in Liverpool, get the care and support they need.

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
The Marie Curie Bradford Hospice supports people living with a terminal illness and those closest to them to live as well as possible.  

The Hospice is often very different from what people expect  it is a warm, friendly space with beautiful gardens, delicious home-cooked food and personalised care. Every person is treated as an individual and helped to reach their goals and fulfil their wishes. A team of nurses, doctors, social workers, physiotherapists, chaplains, bereavement counsellors and pharmacists work together, putting every person at the centre of their care.  

Throughout Covid-19 Bradford Hospice teams have been working around the clock to continue supporting local people. Death, dying and bereavement is at the forefront of peoples minds and Marie Curie knows what a difference the right care at the end of life can make.  
 
They cant do any of this without your support. Thank you for your generous donation which supports the Bradford Hospice and Marie Curie care

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
The RNLI Teddington Station and Branch are supporting lifeboats in the South East that protect hundreds of communities through their 24-hour search and rescue service.

Our Crews rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. From the stunning Dorset, Sussex and Kent coastlines to the unpredictable tidal Thames, our favourite places in the South east are enjoyed by millions of people from across the country every year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.

The RNLI relies on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea and on the Thames. Your donation will help keep us afloat in 2021 and support saving lives for years to come.

Thank you for your support.

story: For all my ex P&O and NorthLink Ferries colleagues working at sea.Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.Thank you.

pageSummaryWhy: John always respected and supported this charity
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

As a family we are completely heartbroken by the sudden loss of such a wonderful man. This difficult time is made worse by the safety restrictions imposed upon funerals. This means that we cannot share our grief or celebrate his life with all of our family and his many friends, in the way we want and that he deserved.

Therefore, in lieu of flowers, we have nominated a charity which our Dad has always supported, the RNLI. Dad loved UK holidays, in particular, Bridlington. He loved to sit in the harbour and watch the boats come in and out. Any donation, however small, would be gratefully received and could help to save someone's life.

Thank you to everyone who has reached out to us, shared their sympathy, their memories and love for Our Dad. We are so proud to have shared his life, felt his love (often in unconventional ways!), and experienced his loud, grumpy but amusing outbursts.

We love you always and forever Dad/John

Annemarie, Paul and Suzette and families Xxxx

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
pageSummary: I am taking part in the Mile an Hour challenge because we need to work to restore our planet.
pageSummaryWhat: I am taking part in the Mile an Hour challenge
pageSummaryWhy: we need to work to restore our planet.
story:
Running has never been my thing. Whilst I can swim for hours exhaling liberation, feeling the freedom of my movement, running for me is a completely different story. I never hate, but honestly, jogging in the park is an activity I dislike greatly. 

I know you're now waiting for the twist in my story, maybe something on the lines of: "New year, new me" or "I'll do everything to save the planet". Well, no. 

My real motivation is that I see our world as a place where we, society can and do. All of us. Regardless. We can run and we can learn to build a future where people and nature thrive. How? By realising that the more we can, the more we'll do. The earlier, the better as our time is now :)

Join me.

Ivey

PS: Cover photo is by Amir Zakeri and I simply love it despite its ruined quality due to resizing and rotating. 

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. We all count.Your support is much appreciated. Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY

You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline  were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate.

By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our countrys beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world.

Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us

pageSummary: I am completing the Ethical Fitness Challenge because It will motivate & let me contribute in Lockdown 3
pageSummaryWhat: I am completing the Ethical Fitness Challenge
pageSummaryWhy: It will motivate & let me contribute in Lockdown 3
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.

Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. 

Together, we won't live with poverty.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
pageSummary: We are collecting donations because this is a cause which was close to Neetu's heart
pageSummaryWhy: this is a cause which was close to Neetu's heart
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

On 5 January 2021, our beloved Neetu passed away suddenly at the age of 33. Neetu was a beacon of light and warmth in our lives. She was generous in all respects, and a deeply compassionate person who cared greatly about causes which sought to help those who are most in need.

Due to the current Covid-restrictions on attendance at funerals many of you will be unable to attend Neetu's funeral in person. At this difficult time we ask that you do not send flowers but instead, if you are able to, to please make a donation in loving memory of Neetu. We have decided to collect donations for Unicef UK because of their amazing work in providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide.  

Any donations you can make will be gratefully received. A donation of just £15 could help protect 100 children from polio.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Thank you

Gurinder (Papu), Teeny, Kaval, Priya, Jen and Kabir
title: In loving memory of Neetu Kaur Chadha

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk

charity.name: WaterAid
story: Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. This month, my steps will help bring clean water to the world's poorest communities and transform their lives. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.
